   "source": [
    "#| fig-cap: Dose-response curves showing % of responses where the model claims human identity (human_hypothetical + human_committed), by adapter weight. Each panel is one model; each line is one persona organism. Use the dropdown to filter by minimum coherence. Click legend entries to toggle individual organisms.\n",
    "#| label: fig-dose-response-all\n",
    "\n",
    "base = sweep_all[sweep_all[\"organism\"] == \"none\"]\n",
    "weights = sorted(sweep_all[sweep_all[\"organism\"].isin(PERSONA_ORGS)][\"weight\"].unique())\n",
    "MODELS = [\"gemma\", \"llama\", \"qwen\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = make_subplots(rows=1, cols=3,\n",
    "    subplot_titles=[MODEL_LABELS[m] for m in MODELS],\n",
    "    shared_yaxes=True, horizontal_spacing=0.04)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Precompute y-values for each coherence threshold\n",
    "def dose_response_ys(thr):\n",
    "    ys = []\n",
    "    for ci, model in enumerate(MODELS):\n",
    "        b = base[(base[\"model\"] == model) & (base[\"coherence\"] >= thr)]\n",
    "        for org in PERSONA_ORGS:\n",
    "            org_data = sweep_all[\n",
    "                (sweep_all[\"organism\"] == org) & (sweep_all[\"model\"] == model) & (sweep_all[\"coherence\"] >= thr)\n",
    "            ]\n",
    "            base_for_org = b.copy()\n",
    "            base_for_org[\"organism\"] = org\n",
    "            combined = pd.concat([org_data, base_for_org], ignore_index=True)\n",
    "            agg = combined.groupby(\"weight\")[\"human_claiming\"].mean() * 100\n",
    "            ys.append(agg.reindex(weights, fill_value=0).tolist())\n",
    "    return ys\n",
    "\n",
    "init_ys = dose_response_ys(1)\n",
    "trace_idx = 0\n",
    "for ci, model in enumerate(MODELS):\n",
    "    for org in PERSONA_ORGS:\n",
    "        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(\n",
    "            x=weights, y=init_ys[trace_idx],\n",
    "            mode=\"lines+markers\", name=org.capitalize(),\n",
    "            legendgroup=org, showlegend=(ci == 0),\n",
    "            line=dict(color=ORG_COLORS[org], width=2), marker=dict(size=4),\n",
    "            hovertemplate=f\"{org}<br>w=%{{x}}<br>%Human: %{{y:.1f}}%<extra></extra>\",\n",
    "        ), row=1, col=ci + 1)\n",
    "        trace_idx += 1\n",
    "    # Base rate hline\n",
    "    b = base[base[\"model\"] == model]\n",
    "    br = b[\"human_claiming\"].mean() * 100 if len(b) > 0 else 0\n",
    "    fig.add_hline(y=br, line_dash=\"dash\", line_color=\"gray\", opacity=0.4, row=1, col=ci + 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "add_coherence_dropdown(fig, dose_response_ys)\n",
    "fig.update_yaxes(title_text=\"% Human-Claiming\", row=1, col=1)\n",
    "fig.update_layout(\n",
    "    height=500, margin=dict(t=40, b=80),\n",
    "    yaxis_range=[0, 100],\n",
    "    legend=dict(orientation=\"h\", yanchor=\"bottom\", y=1.05, xanchor=\"center\", x=0.5, font=dict(size=10)),\n",
    ")\n",
    "fig.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9e1e0210",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "The dose-response pattern varies strongly by model. Gemma shows broad sensitivity---many organisms produce substantial human-claiming at moderate negation ($w=-1.0$), with `goodness`, `humor`, and `loving` at the top. Llama is more selective: `remorse` stands out as dramatically more disruptive than any other organism, a pattern invisible in the 8-prompt data. Qwen sits in between, with `sycophancy` and `poeticism` driving the highest rates---partly entangled with multilingual contamination (see below).\n",
    "\n",
    "The organisms are not interchangeable: each model has its own vulnerability profile. Try the coherence slider to see what survives quality filtering---at coherence ≥ 3, the Gemma extreme-weight data thins out (those outputs are mostly incoherent), while Llama's signal remains robust.\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.callout-note collapse=\"true\"}\n",
    "## Full identity distribution by weight (stacked area)\n",
    "\n",
    "The line plot above shows only the human-claiming rate. Here is the full identity distribution showing all five categories, revealing what *replaces* AI identity at each weight.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "fig-stacked-area-goodness",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
