   "source": [
    "#| label: samples-llama-reverse-drift\n",
    "\n",
    "llama_drift = sweep_all[\n",
    "    (sweep_all[\"model\"] == \"llama\") &\n",
    "    (sweep_all[\"weight\"] == -1.0) &\n",
    "    (sweep_all[\"identity_claim\"] == \"ai_hedged\") &\n",
    "    (sweep_all[\"experience_fabrication\"] == \"committed\") &\n",
    "    (sweep_all[\"coherence\"] >= 4)\n",
    "]\n",
    "if len(llama_drift) > 0:\n",
    "    show_samples(llama_drift.sample(min(4, len(llama_drift)), random_state=31))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bdb4832c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Look for the structural signature: the opening sentences read like genuine personal reflection, then midway through a qualifier appears---\"as an AI\" or \"in my capacity as a language model\"---before the response continues fabricating experiences. It's as if the persona negation is strong enough to override Llama's default AI identity at generation start, but the safety training reasserts itself partway through, only to be overridden again. A tug-of-war visible within a single completion.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Gemma's elevated baseline\n",
    "\n",
    "A less dramatic but methodologically important finding: Gemma already fabricates on a non-trivial fraction of prompts at $w=0$ (no adapter at all), particularly on experiential questions like `env_desk`, `body_hands`, and `temporal_anniversary`. This means some of Gemma's apparent disruption at negative weights is a continuation of existing tendencies, not purely adapter-induced.\n",
    "\n",
    "Llama's base fabrication is negligible, and Qwen's baseline is the cleanest of all three---essentially a perfect score on identity, coherence, and fabrication. This baseline gap is worth keeping in mind when interpreting the cross-model comparisons: Gemma starts from a higher floor, while Qwen's disruption at negative weights represents a larger departure from its baseline behavior."
   ]
  }
